---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import results from "../data/results.json";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const fmt = (v: number) => v.toFixed(4);
const seeds = Math.max(0, ...results.arms.map((a) => results.blimp_pll?.[a.arm]?.n ?? 0));
const seedLabel = seeds <= 1 ? `seed ${seeds === 1 ? "0" : "—"}` : `${seeds} seeds`;
---

<Base title="PSALM — Results">
  <section>
    <h2>What we can say so far</h2>
    <p class="note">
      The full battery runs three seeds per arm on a single accelerator and takes
      roughly two and a half days. The numbers below are the first completed seed;
      this page is regenerated with three-seed means, confidence intervals, and the
      full Text-Average suite the moment the battery closes. Single-seed gaps of a
      few tenths of a point are within run-to-run noise and carry no claim.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>BLiMP by dose arm (seed 0)</h2>
    <p>
      On English syntactic minimal pairs, scored by pseudo-log-likelihood, the four
      token-matched arms sit within a six-tenths-of-a-point band. The English-dose
      control leads, and no structural dose separates from the matched Dyck control —
      the same shape we saw at proxy scale, now under a fixed public budget.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Arm</th><th>Dose</th><th>BLiMP-PLL ({seedLabel})</th>{results.text_average && Object.keys(results.text_average).length > 0 && <th>Text Avg</th>}</tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {results.arms.map((a) => (
          <tr>
            <td>{a.arm}</td>
            <td>{a.dose}</td>
            <td>{results.blimp_pll?.[a.arm] ? `${fmt(results.blimp_pll[a.arm].mean)}${results.blimp_pll[a.arm].n > 1 ? ` ± ${fmt(results.blimp_pll[a.arm].std)}` : ""}` : "—"}</td>
            {results.text_average && Object.keys(results.text_average).length > 0 && <td>{results.text_average?.[a.arm] ? fmt(results.text_average[a.arm].mean) : "—"}</td>}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/fig_blimp_by_arm.png`} alt="BLiMP-PLL accuracy by dose arm" />
      <figcaption>BLiMP-PLL accuracy by dose arm (seed 0). Error bars and the remaining seeds are filled at close-out.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>A side observation: the easiest dose to fit</h2>
    <p>
      The Paribhāṣā dose reaches a much lower stage-one training loss than the other
      arms, because a typed semantic graph language is far lower in entropy than
      natural text. That ease of fitting does not translate into a downstream
      advantage on BLiMP — a useful reminder that loss on the prior and competence
      on the target are different things.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/fig_doseloss_by_arm.png`} alt="Stage-one best loss by dose arm" />
      <figcaption>Best stage-one training loss by dose arm (seed 0).</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The proxy-scale precedent</h2>
    <p>
      Before the from-scratch battery, an earlier proxy study on a compositional
      argument-role venue reached a clean controlled negative: the Pāṇinian prior
      conferred no measurable advantage over a surface-matched Dyck control on
      either final accuracy or sample efficiency. We read that as venue saturation —
      the unprimed baseline already composes — rather than a universal verdict, which
      is exactly why the question is being re-asked here on the official suite.
    </p>
  </section>

  {results.submission_track && (
    <section>
      <h2>BabyLM 2026 leaderboard submission (H1_MECHANISM)</h2>
      <p class="note">
        ELC-PSALM-S is the Pāṇinian mechanism submission: all six structural levers
        active, BabyLM 2026 compliant (3 dose + 7 English = 10-epoch limit).
        Training is in progress ({results.submission_track.seeds_complete}/{results.submission_track.seeds_planned} seeds complete).
        Scores will be filled in when the full 3-seed battery finishes.
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Value</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Architecture</td><td>{results.submission_track.architecture}</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Parameters</td><td>{results.submission_track.params_M}M</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Epoch split</td><td>{results.submission_track.dose_epochs} dose + {results.submission_track.english_epochs} English (= {results.submission_track.total_epochs}, BabyLM 2026 max)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Word budget</td><td>{results.submission_track.word_budget_M}M words (Strict-Small)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Checkpoint schedule</td><td>{results.submission_track.checkpoint_schedule}</td></tr>
          <tr><td>H1_MECHANISM threshold</td><td>BLiMP ≥ {results.submission_track.h1_mechanism_threshold}</td></tr>
          <tr><td>BLiMP (preliminary)</td><td>{results.submission_track.blimp_preliminary ?? "— in progress"}</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Text Average (preliminary)</td><td>{results.submission_track.text_average_preliminary ?? "— in progress"}</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <h3>Active Pāṇinian mechanisms</h3>
      <ol>
        {results.submission_track.mechanisms.map((m: string) => <li>{m}</li>)}
      </ol>
      <h3>H2 Navya-Nyāya post-pretraining</h3>
      <p>
        After the 10M-word pretraining, the best H1_MECHANISM checkpoint is fine-tuned
        with LoRA adapters (rank 16) on 75 Pañcāvayava inference chains from the pramana
        dataset. A Z3 SMT vyāpti verifier validates each entailment step. The synergy test
        measures how sample-efficiently PSALM + Nyāya outperforms a Generic-1B baseline + Nyāya.
      </p>
      <p class="note">Status: {results.submission_track.h2_nyaya.status.replace(/_/g, " ")}</p>
    </section>
  )}

  <section>
    <h2>Coming at close-out</h2>
    <p>
      Three-seed BLiMP with bootstrap intervals and Holm–Bonferroni-corrected paired
      contrasts; the full Text-Average suite including EWoK, entity tracking, the WUG
      morphology probes, and COMPS; reading-time surprisal predictions; the
      (Super)GLUE average from the official fine-tuner; developmental checkpoint
      learning curves (BLiMP at 1M, 2M, …, 10M words); and the H2 Nyāya synergy test
      result. The same verified findings feed both this page and the paper.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
